3:Dynamic treatment regime recommendation is the recipe in Chapter 4 where the gap between "the system produces recommendations" and "the system produces recommendations that meaningfully shape sequential clinical decisions in a way patients and clinicians trust" is the widest. The methodological literature has been mature for two decades. The applied production work has lagged because the gap is not primarily a methods gap. It is an alignment gap (between what the regime optimizes and what the program actually wants), an engagement gap (between what clinicians need to act on a recommendation and what the system surfaces), an evaluation gap (between what OPE can tell you and what you really want to know about future deployment), and a governance gap (between what the regulators require and what most engineering teams are prepared to deliver). The architecture in this recipe addresses each of these gaps deliberately. Most of the addressing is not AWS-specific. Most of it is methodological discipline applied seriously, governance applied seriously, clinician engagement designed deliberately, and patient communication taken seriously. The cloud infrastructure is comparatively easy.
